          <h3>4,000 Years of Dynastic History</h3>
          <p>From bronze age oracle bones to the maritime expeditions of the Ming</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Chinese civilisation is organised by <strong>dynasties</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">朝代</span>) — successive ruling houses from the semi-legendary Xia through the Ming. Each dynasty's contributions to the <a href="/zodiac/">zodiac</a>, <a href="/calendar/">calendar</a>, <a href="/fengshui/">feng shui</a>, <a href="/taoism/">philosophy</a>, and the arts are surveyed here. The narrative ends at the Ming (1644) — the last Han Chinese-ruled dynasty.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="xia">
      <h2>Xia Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">夏朝</span>, c. 2070–1600 BCE)</h2>
      <p>Traditionally China's first dynasty, founded by Yu the Great (<span class="chinese-char">大禹</span>) after controlling the Great Flood. Archaeological evidence remains debated (Erlitou site in Henan is the leading candidate).</p>
      <div class="info-grid">
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">📅</span><div class="info-card-value">夏曆</div><div class="info-card-label">Calendar Origins</div><div class="info-card-desc">The <em>Xia Xiao Zheng</em> describes agricultural activities month by month. The calendar is still called the "Xia calendar."</div></div>
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">🏺</span><div class="info-card-value">Bronze Age</div><div class="info-card-label">Metallurgy</div><div class="info-card-desc">Early bronze production marks the beginning of China's Bronze Age civilisation.</div></div>
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">👑</span><div class="info-card-value">Dynasty</div><div class="info-card-label">Hereditary Rule</div><div class="info-card-desc">Established dynastic succession, replacing the abdication system — the pattern for all subsequent dynasties.</div></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="shang">
      <h2>Shang Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">商朝</span>, c. 1600–1046 BCE)</h2>
      <p>The earliest dynasty confirmed by archaeological evidence, centred on the Yellow River in modern Henan. Its capital Yinxu (<span class="chinese-char">殷墟</span>) yielded extraordinary finds.</p>
      <div class="info-grid">
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">📜</span><div class="info-card-value">甲骨文</div><div class="info-card-label">Oracle Bone Script</div><div class="info-card-desc">Earliest Chinese writing. Contains first <a href="/calendar/">calendar records</a> and the Heavenly Stems/Earthly Branches system.</div></div>
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">🏺</span><div class="info-card-value">832 kg</div><div class="info-card-label">Simuwu Ding</div><div class="info-card-desc">The largest ancient bronze vessel ever found. Shang bronzes reached artistic sophistication unmatched in the ancient world.</div></div>
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">🔮</span><div class="info-card-value">Divination</div><div class="info-card-label">Oracle Bone Reading</div><div class="info-card-desc">Systematic divination (<span class="chinese-char">卜</span>) established the precedent for <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a> and the Chinese metaphysical tradition.</div></div>
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">🕯️</span><div class="info-card-value">Ancestors</div><div class="info-card-label">Ancestral Veneration</div><div class="info-card-desc">Formalised ancestor worship — central to <a href="/spring-festival/">Spring Festival</a> observance to this day.</div></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="zhou">
      <h2>Zhou Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">周朝</span>, 1046–256 BCE)</h2>

      <div class="stat-highlight">
        <div class="stat-highlight-number">~790</div>
        <div class="stat-highlight-text">
          <strong>Years — the longest dynasty.</strong> Divided into Western Zhou (strong central authority) and Eastern Zhou (Spring and Autumn + Warring States periods).
        </div>
