      <h3>The Hundred Schools of Thought (<span class="chinese-char">百家爭鳴</span>)</h3>
      <div class="info-grid">
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">📖</span><div class="info-card-value">儒家</div><div class="info-card-label">Confucianism</div><div class="info-card-desc">Confucius (551–479 BCE) & Mencius — the ethical framework governing Chinese society for two millennia.</div></div>
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">☯️</span><div class="info-card-value">道家</div><div class="info-card-label"><a href="/taoism/">Taoism</a></div><div class="info-card-desc">Laozi & Zhuangzi — natural spontaneity, the Dao, and the alternative to Confucian social ethics.</div></div>
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">⚖️</span><div class="info-card-value">法家</div><div class="info-card-label">Legalism</div><div class="info-card-desc">Han Feizi & Shang Yang — the political philosophy that enabled Qin unification.</div></div>
        <div class="info-card"><span class="info-card-icon">☵</span><div class="info-card-value">陰陽家</div><div class="info-card-label">Yin-Yang School</div><div class="info-card-desc">Zou Yan (305–240 BCE) — systematised <a href="/wuxing/">Five Elements</a> and yin-yang cosmology.</div></div>
